Great question üëç Let‚Äôs break it down step by step with simple words + your Buy and Sell Properties project context:





---



‚ùì Can we create an object of a static class?



üëâ No, we cannot.



A static class in C# is like a toolbox. You don‚Äôt need to make a new toolbox every time; you just directly use the tools inside it.



Since all members inside a static class are shared across the whole application, it doesn‚Äôt make sense to create separate objects.







---



üìñ Definition



Static Class: A class declared with static keyword.



It cannot be instantiated (no object creation).



All methods and variables inside it must be static.



Stored in memory only once for the whole application.









---



üèóÔ∏è Project Use (Buy & Sell Properties App)



Example where you might use a static class:



You create a static class called AppConstants to store:



Roles ‚Üí Admin, Owner, Buyer



Property Status ‚Üí Available, Sold, Pending







public static class AppConstants

{

    public const string RoleAdmin = "Admin";

    public const string RoleOwner = "Owner";

    public const string RoleBuyer = "Buyer";



    public static string ApplicationName = "Property Marketplace";

}



üëâ Anywhere in your app, instead of creating objects, you just call:



if(user.Role == AppConstants.RoleAdmin)

{

    // Admin can approve property

}



So:



No object needed.



Easy to use everywhere.







---



‚öñÔ∏è Trade-offs



‚úÖ Pros:



Memory efficient (loaded only once).



Easy to share constants/utilities everywhere.



Good for global helper methods (e.g., logging, validation).





‚ùå Cons:



No flexibility (cannot create different copies/objects).



Hard to test in unit tests (since everything is global).



If misused, can make code tightly coupled (everyone depends on it).







---



üíº Business Impact in your Project



Using static classes for constants, helpers, utilities makes your Buy & Sell Properties app faster and cleaner.



Example: When checking roles or statuses, all developers use the same central place ‚Üí fewer bugs, easier maintenance.



But for things that change per user (like session, property details, transactions), you must not use static classes. Otherwise, one user‚Äôs data could overwrite another‚Äôs ‚Üí big problem for buyers/sellers.







---



‚úÖ In short:



You cannot create objects of static classes.



In your property app, you use them for constants, role checks, helpers.



They give speed and consistency, but you must not use them for user-specific data.







