//////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////What is filter and types.
Definition (In very simple words):

> ASP.NET MVC Filter is a custom class where you can write custom logic to excute before an after an action method executes.


Think of them like security guards or quality checkers standing at different doors of your MVC pipeline.


---

‚öôÔ∏è Why we use Filters:

‚úÖ To perform common logic across multiple controllers/actions (without repeating code).
‚úÖ To apply cross-cutting concerns such as:

Authentication & Authorization

Logging

Exception handling

Caching

Validation



---

üß© Types of Filters in ASP.NET Core

Filter Type When It Runs Common Use Example

1Ô∏è‚É£ Authorization Filter Before anything else (first checkpoint) Checks if user is authorized [Authorize]
2Ô∏è‚É£ Resource Filter Before & after model binding Handle caching, performance optimization Custom caching filter
3Ô∏è‚É£ Action Filter Before & after controller action executes Logging, validation, modify input/output [ActionFilter]
4Ô∏è‚É£ Exception Filter When an exception occurs Handle exceptions globally [CustomExceptionFilter]
5Ô∏è‚É£ Result Filter Before & after result (like View or JSON) executes Modify or format result [ResultFilter]



---

üíª Example (Custom Action Filter)

using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Filters;
using System.Diagnostics;

public class LogActionFilter : ActionFilterAttribute
{
    private Stopwatch stopwatch;

    public override void OnActionExecuting(ActionExecutingContext context)
    {
        stopwatch = Stopwatch.StartNew();
        Console.WriteLine($"Action {context.ActionDescriptor.DisplayName} started at {DateTime.Now}");
    }

    public override void OnActionExecuted(ActionExecutedContext context)
    {
        stopwatch.Stop();
        Console.WriteLine($"Action {context.ActionDescriptor.DisplayName} finished in {stopwatch.ElapsedMilliseconds} ms");
    }
}

Usage:

[LogActionFilter]
public class PropertyController : ControllerBase
{
    [HttpGet("get-properties")]
    public IActionResult GetProperties()
    {
        return Ok(new { message = "Property list fetched successfully!" });
    }
}


---

üè† Project Example (Buy & Sell Properties App):

Scenario:
In your property application, you need to log each API call made by users to track performance and detect issues.

‚úÖ You can use an Action Filter to log every request.
‚úÖ You can use an Exception Filter to log and return friendly messages when something crashes.
‚úÖ You can use a Result Filter to format all responses in a standard JSON format.


---

‚öñÔ∏è Trade-Off:

‚úÖ Pros: Clean, reusable, centralized logic (no code duplication).

‚ö†Ô∏è Cons: Too many filters can make debugging hard ‚Äî because code runs before/after controller automatically.



---

üíº Business Impact:

Using filters helps your project:

Improve security (Authorization filters)

Improve user experience (Exception filters for friendly errors)

Improve maintainability (Centralized logic)

Improve performance tracking (Action filters)
