//////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
ùêÄùêùùêùùêíùê¢ùêßùê†ùê•ùêûùê≠ùê®ùêß vs ùêÄùêùùêùùêíùêúùê®ùê©ùêûùêù vs ùêÄùêùùêùùêìùê´ùêöùêßùê¨ùê¢ùêûùêßùê≠ in C# Dependency Injection
Do you really know the difference? 

Whenever a service is requested, the DI Container must decide:
 ‚û°Ô∏è Create a new instance?
 ‚û°Ô∏è Or reuse an existing one?

That decision depends on the lifetime defined when you register the service.
Here‚Äôs a quick refresher:
ùêÄùêùùêùùêíùê¢ùêßùê†ùê•ùêûùê≠ùê®ùêß
‚Ä¢ A single instance is created the first time it's requested (or during ConfigureServices if specified).
‚Ä¢ The same instance is used throughout the application's lifetime.

ùêÄùêùùêùùêíùêúùê®ùê©ùêûùêù
‚Ä¢ A new instance is created once per request.
‚Ä¢ Ideal for web apps where services share state per HTTP request.

ùêÄùêùùêùùêìùê´ùêöùêßùê¨ùê¢ùêûùêßùê≠
‚Ä¢ A new instance every time the service is requested.
‚Ä¢ Best for lightweight, stateless operations.

When to Use What?
‚úîÔ∏è Use Transient for short-lived, stateless services.
 ‚úîÔ∏è Use Scoped when you want to maintain state within a request.
 ‚úîÔ∏è Use Singleton for app-wide services like logging, caching, and configuration.

Making the right choice can improve performance and prevent memory issues.

 What‚Äôs your default choice and why? Let‚Äôs discuss!
